{"cursor":"17380","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Tunable diode laser absorption spectroscopy' ('TDLAS') is a technique for\nmeasuring the concentration of certain species such as methane, water vapor and\nmany more, in a gaseous mixture using tunable diode lasers and laser absorption\nspectrometry. The advantage of TDLAS over other techniques for concentration\nmeasurement is its ability to achieve very low detection limits (of the order of\nppb). Apart from concentration, it is also possible to determine the\ntemperature, pressure, velocity and mass flux of the gas under\nobservation. D. T. Cassidy and J. Reid, \"Atmospheric pressure monitoring of\ntrace gases using tunable diode lasers,\" Appl. Opt. 21(7), 1185â1190\n(1982) P. Werle, F. Slemr, K. Maurer, R. Kormann, R. Mucke, and B.\nJanker, \"Near- and mid-infrared laser-optical sensors for gas analysis,\" Opt.\nLas. Eng. 37(2â3), 101â114 (2002) TDLAS is by far the most common laser\nbased absorption technique for quantitative assessments of species in gas phase.\n","linknr":180,"url":"Tunable_Diode_Laser_Absorption_Spectroscopy","recorded":1362569877,"links":16,"instances":["spectroscopy"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Spectroscopy","Gas technologies"],"headings":["Working","Basic principles","Limitations and means of improvements","Applications","Notes","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/1/3/f136969348f9033a150b809209a6f221.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/c/c/ccc9910408e42c4635a42f08b5d48b76.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/9/5/795091e182278cbc6864fcb2d8f22cd2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/2/0/d20caec3b48a1eef164cb4ca81ba2587.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/1/4/914d0606ff1cc3162b88adaa8547160d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/2/6/e26124f49782b87e4aeebc22b8670ae4.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/9/1/691605ee40779aec004ebf721a9928d3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/d/3/6d3fb1243abbe7c6cb01ba1a09e68ae8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/